5|$|The Bilbie {{family were}} also {{involved}} in clock making. In 1749 Thomas Biblie (senior) was asked to make a set of chimes for Cullompton church. Thomas II worked on clock mechanisms to play tunes on <b>church</b> <b>bells</b> at East Coker and also at Beaminster. Thomas Castleman is recorded as having made a clock for Cullompton Church in 1811 {{at a cost of}} £55.|$|E
50|$|Inside, {{the church}} is quite profusely {{decorated}} with medieval frescos. These seem all {{to have been made}} by the so-called Master of the Passion of Christ. They depict scenes from the Passion of Christ, several saints and some scenes depicting devils and women. Among the furnishings of the church, only the base of the baptismal font and the <b>church</b> <b>bell</b> are medieval (12th and 13th centuries). The <b>church</b> <b>bell</b> is supposedly the largest 13th century <b>church</b> <b>bell</b> in Sweden. Other furnishings date mostly from the 18th century and the late 19th century.|$|R
